This is still terrifying, even 50 years later...the character development around Nell is incredible. The viewer is left to question whether it is the house or her deteriorating mental state...reminds me a lot of Repulsion in some ways.
Maybe I missed something but the whole plot seemed pointless to me. Characters were poorly developed and aside from a few moments that were intended as comic relief, I was bored.
Great soundtrack, looks amazing, thoroughly enjoyable. The "tender" moments, though, get pretty corny pretty fast.

Although I love satirical teen movies as much as anyone else, something about this movie didn't quite grab me. It was enjoyable, don't get me wrong, but something about it was trying too hard. Rose McGowan is great in it, as expected, but the dialogue was too forced and it wasn't quite pointed enough to be truly effective.

I first watched this movie with my ex-boyfriend when I was 18, and I don't know I how I forgot how absolutely brilliant and fucked up it is. These characters and their lives are so seemingly normal, so regular...that to see them disintegrating in their private lives is somehow sickeningly comforting. It's like watching the condescending yuppie moms I serve brunch to crumble. Highly, highly recommended.

While at times difficult to watch, The Elephant Man is a brilliant portrait of a gentle soul subjected to the horrors of human nature. Lynch does a wonderful job of juxtaposing Merrick's "freakshow" beginnings with his newfound notoriety in high society, allowing the viewer to come to terms with the fact that there is really no difference at all. While not stereotypically Lynchian, the dream sequences in particular were beautiful and extremely well done.
